<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/swccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Gimli   Farin   Fror   Gloin        OH MY (A look at the Dwarf culture)<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(4.72)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9579'>Pete "Thorbolter" Steinmetz</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9579&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> March 5, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Gimli&#8230;Farin&#8230;Fror&#8230;Gloin&#8230;OH MY (A look at the Dwarf culture)<br>
<br>
Throughout fantasy (AD&D, DaoC, Baldur&#8217;s Gate, etc) dwarves have always been portrayed as a hardy race.  Lord of the Rings is no exception.  Having been written so long ago, it may be the foundation of how we think the Dwarf race should be portrayed.  In any case, we will discuss the strengths and weaknesses of the Dwarf culture in LoTR CCG.  I feel I am somewhat of an expert in this area as Dwarves is practically the only race I play and probably the only one in the entire state of Oklahoma who plays them.   Onward to the Dwarves&#8230;.<br>
<br>
Companions are the bread and butter of our deck.  With the first release, we had three Dwarf companions to choose from.  Gimli, Farin, and the dwarven red shirt guard.  Mines of Moria introduce us to two more companions, Fror and Gloin.<br>
<br>
Gimli, Dwarf of Erebor &#8211; Damage +1.  Fellowship: Add two shadow to place a card from hand beneath your draw deck.<br>
<br>
Gimli, Son of Gloin &#8211; Damage +1. Skirmish: Exert Gimli to make him strength +2.<br>
<br>
Gimli, Dwarf of the Mountain race &#8211; Damage +1. Each underground site&#8217;s Shadow number is &#8211;2.<br>
<br>
Farin, Dwarven Emissary &#8211; To play spot a Dwarf.  While skirmishing an Orc, Farin is strength +2.<br>
<br>
Fror, Gimli&#8217;s Kinsman &#8211; To play, spot a Dwarf.  While skirmishing an Uruk-hai, Fror is strength +3.<br>
<br>
Gloin, Friend to Thorin &#8211; For each Dwarf tale you can spot, Gloin is strength +1.<br>
<br>
Dwarf Guard &#8211; To play, spot a dwarf.<br>
<br>
So many options, but only so much space in your deck.  The Dwarf Guards are the only non-unique cards which means you can have 4 of them out at same time and others only 1 in play/dead pile, others must be discarded.<br>
<br>
They all cost two points to play, except for the guards, which cost 1.  This allows us to start with two of the unique companions or one unique and two guards.  I prefer to start with two unique and draw for the guards.  I like to play with the rare Gimli as one of my starting companions because 1) it is rare and having multiple copies is uneconomical 2) Gimli is after all the foundation of the Dwarf culture in LoTR CCG 3) best Dwarf companion.  I also used to start with Farin, but because he is uncommon and Gloin is the other rare Dwarf, I will start with Gloin from now on.  So we have Gimli and Gloin as our starting companions.  This leaves us with Farin, Fror and Dwarf Guard.  More people play Orcs so Farin has more upside than Fror, which means I want to get him out quicker than Fror so I will play with 3 Farins and 2 Frors.  As for Dwarf Guards, in the past I played with 2-3, mostly used as red shirt sacrifices.  I will continue this strategy but will limit Dwarf Guards to 1-2 in my deck.  Other companions that work well in dwarf decks are Sam (helps remove burdens and picks up the ring if Frodo can&#8217;t handle it), Aragorn (great cannon fodder at last moment with defender ability) and Legolas (having an archer is always handy).<br>
<br>
Conditions are always nice to have.  They can either help boost your Dwarfs or hurt your opponent.  Stating the obvious I know.  Let&#8217;s look at them.<br>
<br>
Dwarven Heart &#8211; When you play this condition, heal bearer up to two times.  At the start of each of your turns, exert bearer.  OK, so great immediate affect on bearer of this condition, but the next turns could mean the death unless you have a way to remove it.  I find this condition quite useless, haven&#8217;t found a deck yet that this will work in.<br>
<br>
Greatest Kingdom of My People &#8211; Tale.  Exert a Dwarf to play this condition.  Plays to your support area.  Each time your opponent plays an Orc, that player discards the top card of his or her draw deck.  This card is the best condition in my opinion.  In a discard deck, this card is a definite must.  Even in a non-discard deck, this card is very useful as there are two types of Orcs and you are sure to run across them in a tournament.  And because it is a Tale, Gloin will gain +1 strength while it is in play.<br>
<br>
Let Them Come! &#8211; Plays to your support area.  Each time a dwarf wins a skirmish against an Orc, discard that Orc.  Discard this condition if a dwarf loses a skirmish.  The first affect is great, you win you can discard another orc before someone else goes into battle with it.  Only problem is the losing part.  Dwarves tend to lose, especially the guards so bye bye condition.  Very useful if your local area metagame is Orc which may be the case here soon with MoM, but I am not so sure about this card in a tournament deck.  One of those middle of the ground cards where you have to be the judge whether or not it will fit in your deck.<br>
<br>
Lord of Moria &#8211; Plays to your support area.  Each Dwarf is Damage +1.  This is a non-unique card which means you can have 4 of them out at once.  I have never played with 4 but have played with two and did get them both out.  This card ranks right below Greatest Kingdom of My People as far as conditions go.  Especially against those nast Nazgul fierce decks.  Kill it the first go round and you won&#8217;t see it again.  And it affects all of your dwarves too.  Very good card for all kinds of Dwarf decks.<br>
<br>
Stairs of Kazad-dum- Tale.  Plays to your support area. While a dwarf skirmishes a Moria minion, that Dwarf is strength +1.  Before MoM, this card was ok as far as usefulness goes.  But with MoM, we will see a lot of Moria shadow which means this card becomes very important.  It isn&#8217;t unique so you can have all four of them out at once if you like.  And it is a Tale, so Gloin gets a +1 boost in strength.  The only thing I don&#8217;t like about this card is that you are limiting yourself, your deck, because this card is only useful against Moria.  Again, another call by the deck builder.  May be worth it to throw one in a deck, if not for anything just to give Gloin a permanent +1.<br>
<br>
Beneath the Mountains &#8211; Tale.  Plays to your support area.  Fellowship: Discard the top three cards from your draw deck to play a Dwarf weapon from your discard pile.  I am not sold on this rare.  Sure it is a Tale that adds to Gloins numbers but to discard three from top of your deck to play a weapon from your discard pile?  I don&#8217;t know.  The only advantage besides Gloin I see this condition working in is a Dwarf weapon deck, but I still think that is stretching it.  Those three cards are more important to me than a dwarf axe.<br>
<br>
Endurance of Dwarves &#8211; Bearer must be a dwarf.  Skirmish: Discard this condition to make bearer strength +1.  (this adds +1 to vitality while beared by a Dwarf).  Very handy as Dwarves only have 3 vitality as it is.  But with all the strength boosters, hopefully only your red shirt guards are dieing, not the others.  I have never had a problem with mine dieing off except for the bad card draws of course.  This is another one of those middle of the ground cards where you have to make the call.  Personally, I don&#8217;t see these fitting into my decks as I would rather have strength boosters.  These would be good in a Shoulder to Shoulder deck though.<br>
<br>
Golden Light on the Land &#8211; To play, spot a Dwarf.  Plays to your support area.  At a site which is not underground, each Moria Orc&#8217;s twilight cost is +2.  Discard this condition during the regroup phase.  Again another specific race card.  Great against Moria but is it worth having in your tournament deck?  Maybe if there are a lot of Moria decks in your area but for the most part it isn&#8217;t worth it, especially since you lose it in the regroup phase.<br>
<br>
Great Work Begun There &#8211; Tale.  Plays to your support area.  Each time you play a Dwarf, you may discard the top two cards from your draw deck to take a Dwarf event into hand from discard pile.  OK, first I will mention Gloin will get his token +1 strength.   I don&#8217;t like the fact that you have to discard two cards to get a card from discard pile, but your essentially only discarding one card.  Not a bad card to have, especially if you rely on certain event cards in your deck, depends on your deck focus.  If you were playing a discard deck, and already used your Nobody Tosses a Dwarf cards, then this card would be very handy to get some of them back to rid your opponents deck of cards.  The key to this card is timing though.  This also supports Gloin, so may be worth having at least one in a deck.<br>
<br>
Make Light of Burdens &#8211; Plays to your support area.  Maneuver:  Exert a dwarf companion and discard the top three cards from your draw deck to discard either a shadow condition from a dwarf or a weather condition.  OK, finally, a dwarf card to get rid of conditions.  But man, what a price we have to pay.  Not only do we have to exert a dwarf companion, we have to give up three cards as well.  Sheesh.  But in a dwarf only deck, this is a must have card, at least two of them.  But I would only use this as a last resort when you can&#8217;t live with the condition you are facing any longer.  Don&#8217;t use this willy nilly.<br>
<br>
Realm of Dwarrowdwelf &#8211; Plays to your support area.  Skirmish:  Discard the top three cards from your draw deck to make a dwarf strength +1 (limit +3) and if underground damage +1 (limit +3).  OK, call me crazy here but why in the heck would I do this, especially since I am likely to discard axe strike, flurry of their blows or cleaving blow.  And it is a unique card too so you can only have one out at a time.  It isn&#8217;t even a Tale, so can&#8217;t even play this to support Gloin.  I don&#8217;t like this card, no sir, don&#8217;t like it.  Did I mention this is a Rare.  What a waste of Rare.<br>
<br>
Till Durin Wakes Again &#8211; Tale.  Plays to support area.  Each time a Dwarf companion moves from an underground site, you may heal that dwarf.  OK, this is a Tale that does good to Gloin, and it heals your Dwarves at sites 4 and 5.  Not too shabby at all.  May not fit in all decks, but in a pure offense, survival deck, this is a very nice fit.  Did I mention this is a common?  Maybe the useless Realm should be a common and Till Durin Wakes should be a Rare.  Oh well, I don&#8217;t make the cards.<br>
<br>
Well, that does it for the Dwarf conditions.  Tales are good for Gloin, but there aren&#8217;t many to choose from and only one that is playable in all decks.  Only one condition removal card but it the high price you pay worth it?  On to Posessions.<br>
<br>
Posessions aren&#8217;t necessary in Dwarf decks, but they are one of the main reasons people make Dwarf decks as possessions are pretty useful.  And in MoM, they add more without detracting from the existing.  Very nice.<br>
<br>
Gimli&#8217;s Battle Axe &#8211; Bearer must be Gimli.  Damage +1.  Each time Gimli wins a skirmish, you may wound an orc.  Not bad stats.  Damage +1 and wounding an orc can come in handy.  It all depends on your deck strategy of course.  If you play a discard deck, this axe won&#8217;t fit in well at all.  Any other deck and this axe is excellent.<br>
<br>
Gimli&#8217;s Helm &#8211; Bearer must be Gimli.  He takes no more than 1 wound during each skirmish phase.  Skirmish:  Discard Gimli&#8217;s helm to prevent all wounds to him.  OK, now Gimli has something that is worth wearing in any deck.  Definitely a good possession.  I only play with one but two might be better.  Depends on your deck size and limits.<br>
<br>
Dwarven Axe &#8211; Bearer must be a dwarf.  Each time a players minion loses a skirmish to bearer, that player discards the top card from draw deck.  A must card in a discard deck.  Adds +2 strength to bearer as well.  So very good in all other dwarf decks.  And if you play with Gimlis Axe, play with just one Gimli Axe.  That way you can play a dwarf axe on gimli til his axe comes up and simply transfer this possession to another dwarf.  Not too bad.<br>
<br>
Dwarven Armor &#8211; Bearer must be dwarf.  Bearer may not be overwhelmed unless his strength is tripled.  Again, not too bad.  I played with these in my decks as a third focus.  Defense of the dwarves wasn&#8217;t my goal, it was the offense ability.  This isn&#8217;t a bad possession if it fits into your deck style.  <br>
<br>
Dwarven Bracers &#8211; Bearer must be a dwarf. If bearer is about to take a wound, discard this possession to prevent that wound.  Also adds +1 strength.  OK, I like this simply because it has a similar effect like Gimli&#8217;s Helm, adds +1 stremgth, and can be on any dwarf.  This is like a defense/offense possession combined.  I would replace these for the dwarven armor.  Again, depends on your deck style.<br>
<br>
Hand Axe &#8211; Bearer must be a dwarf.  This weapon may be borne in addition to 1 other hand weapon.  Archery:  Discard this weapon to make the fellowship archery total +1.  Also adds +1 strength.  FYI, the Dwarven Axe, Gimli&#8217;s Axe and the Hand Axe are all hand weapons.  You play with axes and you play with hand axes for sure.  A very nice card.  And to add archery when you need to is a very nice addition.  I like this card.  Three will be in my deck.<br>
<br>
Some nice possessions and only two rares.  I was a little disappointed that Gloin didn&#8217;t have a possession that he could pass on to Gimli, but you can&#8217;t have everything.  Overall, I like the Dwarven Axe, the Hand Axe and the Bracers for Dwarf possessions.  They would fit nicely in any deck.  On to Allies.<br>
<br>
Allies are few and far between in the dwarf culture.  But yet still are somewhat useful.<br>
<br>
Grimir, Dwarven Elder &#8211; Fellowship: Exert Grimir to shuffle a Dwarf event from your discard pile into your draw deck.  Very handy to get those events back into draw deck.  Also nice to keep your deck cards cycled, by that I mean, less chance of running out of cards before your opponent.  Card advantage.  And if you have Elrond in your deck, he will heal Grimir each turn which means you can shuffle a card into your deck each turn.  Very nice indeed.  I always play with 2-3 of him in my deck.<br>
<br>
Thrarin, Dwarven Smith &#8211; Maneuver:  Exert Thrarin to allow him to participate in archery fire and skirmishes until the regroup phase.  Elrond can also heal him but if you are exerting him, you aredoing it more than likely because you ran out of red shirt guards and need a red shirt engineer..er smith.  He is good if you need last minute backup but that is really all he is good for.  I used him before MoM, but now with MoM, no need to use him with the two additional companions.<br>
<br>
That&#8217;s it, no more allies to play here.  Nothing to see, move along.  OK, I will mention Elrond.  To play him you have to spot an Elf or Gandalf.  And he allows you to draw cards and heals every round all allies at site 3.  Not too bad to give you card advantage, to heal Grimir to give you even more card advantage.  And you can play the new Gandalf, The Grey Pilgrim to give you even that much more card advantage which will allow you to play Elrond which will allow you to heal Grimir.  A small three card  combo.  As long as you only use Gandalf for card advantage and not take on minions, I think it will work well.  OK, finally, on to the long list of Events.<br>
<br>
In order to keep this list as short as possible, I am going to combine event cards.  Events are a staple of any Free Peoples deck.  Some are good in all decks, some are good in a few decks, and some are just no good at all.  Hopefully I will cover them all to your satisfaction without dragging on and on.<br>
<br>
Axe Strike, Battle Fury, Cleaving Blow, Their Halls of Stone, Flurry of Blows &#8211; These cards add either strength or damage or both and have various modifiers to make it more.  I don&#8217;t like to exert if I don&#8217;t have to, so that leaves Cleaving Blow out of the good mix.  I don&#8217;t like to spend shadow if I don&#8217;t have to, so that leaves Battle Fury out of the good mix.  I play with axes, so defiantly Axe Strike.  I will start using hand Axes, so definitely Flurry of Blows (I&#8217;ll make the exception and spend 1 shadow with this card).  That leaves us with Halls.  If I am making a pure offense deck, then definitely this card as now I will have 12 dwarf bonus cards, bring it on Balrog.  But if I am not all offense like a discard, I will leave out the halls.  Its all in your deck style of course.<br>
<br>
Delving and Tidings of Erebor &#8211; Both allow you to draw cards.  One you have to exert a Dwarf and we hate to do that.  The other allows us to do it during the regroup phase and our opponent can spend 3 shadow to prevent us from drawing.  I like this option better.  I would rather spend 1 shadow and give opportunity for Shadow player to remove 3 shadow from his pool to prevent us from doing it.  Either way, we either get 3 cards or we removed two from the pool (we gave 1 so really we only remove two).  I like this card and will play with two in any dwarf deck, more if I am playing a twilight denial deck of sorts or a card drawing machine deck.<br>
<br>
Halls of My Home &#8211; This is another exert a dwarf event so already I don&#8217;t like it.  But it does allow you to look at top three cards of any deck (yours, your opponents), put two back in any order and discard a shadow.  This is great if you want to see the top three cards of your opponents deck, and a great way to get rid of any one shadow card (bye bye Lurtz).  It is also good for you if you need fellowship cards.  You can look at your top three cards, discard a shadow card, and decide if a double move is in the cards for you or not this turn.<br>
<br>
Here Lies Balin, Son of Fundin &#8211; Another exertion card.  But you do get to wound two orcs or one twice for the price of one wound on yourself.  Not too bad especially if used at site 9 for the win or to keep Frodo from being overwhelmed.<br>
<br>
Mithril Shaft &#8211; I am not sure I like this cad.  Still have yet to find a reason for it except maybe a last minute game winner card.  But still, why would it be in a deck.  To discard cards and add shadow, just doesn&#8217;t seem like a good strategy to me.<br>
<br>
Nobody Tosses a Dwarf &#8211; OK, this is one of my favorite event cards but mainly because I like discard decks.  This card is the staple of all dwarf discard decks.  Win a skirmish and opponent discards 3 from top of deck.  I especially like it when I get 2 or 3 on initial draw or save them up and make them discard 6-12 cards all at once.  The look on their face is priceless.<br>
<br>
Still Draws Breath &#8211; Not a bad card for healing your dwarves.  But Dwarves are more for offense than defense and this is more of a defense card.  I like the condition Till Durin Wakes Again better for healing than this card.<br>
<br>
Wealth of Moria &#8211; This card ranks just below Mithril Shaft for event cards.  I don&#8217;t want to reveal my top three cards and only keep free peoples.  What if I got unlucky and had 3 shadow right on top and now they are all gone.  Sheesh.  Find a use, let me know.<br>
<br>
Disquiet of Our People &#8211; A dwarf can become defender?  Sweet.  Not too shabby.  And if we spot an ocr a defender +2?  OK, Orcs bring it on.  My dwarven red shirt guard is defender +2.  This card won&#8217;t fit in all decks, but in a offense race to site 9 deck, surely 2 can squeeze in a deck.<br>
<br>
And finally, What Are We Waiting For &#8211; I really like this card a lot.  I see a lot of potential.  Make your opponet draw two cards then either discard two shadow cards or skip their shadow phase.  Sweet Mary this is good .  None of those popular dwarf exertions to use this card, and only one shadow to use it?  Cool.  And what if I play the first one, he draws two cards, elects to skip his shadow phase and keep his shadow cards in hand.  But then I play two more and he draws four cards and has to discard four shadow cards since he is already skipping his shadow phase?  Not too bad if his shadow deck is stronger than his fellowship deck.<br>
<br>
So as you can see, Event cards can pump your dwarves up and hurt your opponents.  Just what all good event cards can do.<br>
<br>
A lot of cards to choose from.  The most popular dwarf decks are the discard decks.  But with MoM, it will be easier to make a race to 9 dwarf deck.  I will let you know how mine fare.  Good luck to all and may Durin watch over you and your deck.<br>
